<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,1157,2015]" pageId="1" pageNumber="48">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[197,330,1811,1835]" pageId="1" pageNumber="48">Host plant.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName box="[338,561,1811,1835]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Brassicaceae" genus="Lepidium" kingdom="Plantae" order="Brassicales" pageId="1" pageNumber="48" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="latifolium">
<emphasis box="[338,561,1811,1835]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="48">Lepidium latifolium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
L. (
<taxonomicName box="[610,761,1811,1835]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Brassicaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Brassicales" pageId="1" pageNumber="48" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Brassicaceae</taxonomicName>
), commonly known as Virginia or broadleaved or perennial pepperweed, or tall whitetop.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,1157,2015]" pageId="1" pageNumber="48">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[197,437,1882,1907]" pageId="1" pageNumber="48">Relation to the host.</emphasis>
In May (spring), leaves of rosettes/bolting plants were distorted along the main vein and were slightly rolled according to their longitudinal axis. In June (late spring-early summer), attacked plants were more stunted and shorter than healthy ones but more leaves were observed (
<figureCitation box="[993,1062,1955,1979]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="3.[151,250,903,926]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,193,882]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[151,1436,193,882]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 2. Lepidium latifolium L.: leaf deformations (courtesy of Gerber E., CABI Europe—Switzerland)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/210177/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="48">
Fig. 
<number box="[1045,1062,1955,1979]" pageId="1" pageNumber="48" value="2.0">2</number>
</figureCitation>
). Flowers appeared to be affected by the presence of mites: pink for non-infested plants and dull white for infested plants.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
